    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Axes to be used in case of fire. They are standard equipment of firefighters and are also often found in public buildings; part of the head and heft may be painted red.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000005711/Blackburn, Illustrated Encyclopedia of Woodworking Handtools (1974)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Bijlen die voornamelijk in openbare gebouwen worden aangetroffen en waarvan een gedeelte van het blad en soms het handvat rood is geschilderd. Ze zijn bedoeld om te worden gebruikt bij brand.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
